{{BLP sources|date=May 2011}} {{Infobox comedian | name = Neil Delamere | image = Neil delamere.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Delamere in 2013 | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1979 | birth_place = [[Edenderry]], [[County Offaly]], Ireland | death_date = | death_place = | medium = | nationality = Irish | active = | genre = | subject = | influences = | influenced = | spouse = | domesticpartner = | notable_work = | signature = | website = [http://www.neildelamere.com/ Official website] | footnotes = | module = }} '''Neil Delamere''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|d|ɛ|l|ə|m|i|ər}} {{respell|DEL|ə-meer}}; born 1979) is an [[Irish people|Irish]] comedian.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/7100/Comedy-review-Neil-Delamere.5596325.jp|title=Comedy review: Neil Delamere|last=Grat|first=Martin|date= 28 August 2009|work=[[The Scotsman]]|accessdate=14 May 2011}}</ref> He is a regular on [[The Blame Game (BBC)|Factbook]] and is represented by [[Off the Kerb]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Artist Pages: Neil Delamere|url=http://www.offthekerb.co.uk/neil-delamere/|publisher=[[Off the Kerb]]|accessdate=23 August 2013}}</ref>
==Brief profile== Delamere is from [[Edenderry]], [[County Offaly]]. He has a degree in Computer Applications from [[Dublin City University]] (DCU), where his portrait is displayed in the university's library amongst other famous graduates. He began his career in 2004 at the [[Edinburgh Festival]]. Since then he has worked for both [[Raidió Teilifís Éireann]] (RTÉ) and the [[BBC]], in programmes such as the BBC comedy series ''[[Dave's One Night Stand|One Night Stand]]'', BBC radio and television panel quiz ''[[The Blame Game (radio)|The Blame Game]]'' and RTÉ topical comedy show ''[[The Panel (Irish TV series)|The Panel]]''. He hosts ''[[Neil Delamere's Just For Laughs]]'', a comedy television show in which he interviews acts performing at the Montreal Festival. He featured on ''Michael McIntyre's Comedy Roadshow'' on 4 July 2009. Delamere made his debut appearance on Radio Five Live's panel show ''[[Fighting Talk]]'', broadcast on 11 December 2010, and won. Since his first appearance on the show, Delamere has made numerous appearances on the Sony award-winning sports show. {{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}
In 2011, he hosted ''The Only Viking in the Village'' on RTÉ, in which he explored his Viking roots and informed viewers that the Vikings poured urine on their clothes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.herald.ie/entertainment/tv-radio/neils-notso-horrible-history-the-only-viking-in-the-village-2949575.html|title=Neil's not-so horrible history the only viking in the village|date=30 November 2011|accessdate=30 November 2011|work=Evening Herald}}</ref> The show was nominated in the factual category for an Irish Film and Television Award, and won. He has stood in for [[John Murray (Irish broadcaster)|John Murray]] on [[RTÉ Radio 1]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/2012/0223/delamaren.html|title=Neil Delamere to Present John Murray Show|date=23 February 2012|accessdate=23 February 2012|work=RTÉ Ten}}</ref>
He presented the comedy documentary ''There's Something about Patrick'' which aired on 14 March 2013 on [[RTÉ 1]]. In the documentary Delamere travels the length and breadth of Ireland (and beyond) to meet experts, historians and [[St Patrick’s Day]] revellers, to discover the truth about the Irish patron saint.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.rte.ie/presspack/2013/03/14/theres-something-about-patrick/|title= THERE’S SOMETHING ABOUT PATRICK|date=|work=RTE.ie|accessdate=21 March 2013 }}</ref>
Delamere also works for the Irish independent and national radio station, [[Today FM]] where he presents his own show titled "Neil Delamere's Sunday Best" which airs every Sunday from 11{{nbsp}}am to 1{{nbsp}}pm.
